00:38:43.520 --> 00:38:44.978
if I'm in a
collectivistic culture,

00:38:44.978 --> 00:38:47.340
whereas in individualistic
cultures, my sense of self

00:38:47.340 --> 00:38:49.600
is much more me
as an individual.

00:38:49.600 --> 00:38:52.300
Yes, I'm part of the group, but
that's a less central focus.

00:38:52.300 --> 00:38:54.050
This is a broad
generalization, of course.

00:38:54.050 --> 00:38:55.740
There's massive
individual differences

00:38:55.740 --> 00:38:57.370
within both kinds of cultures.

00:38:57.370 --> 00:38:59.245
But I think that's what
you're talking about.

00:38:59.245 --> 00:39:02.450
And so yeah, if you're in a
collectivistic society, then

00:39:02.450 --> 00:39:05.216
absolutely, feeling a sense
of pride in the collective

00:39:05.216 --> 00:39:06.840
can serve the same
functions as feeling

00:39:06.840 --> 00:39:08.260
an individual sense of pride.

00:39:08.260 --> 00:39:10.254
Yeah.

00:39:10.254 --> 00:39:11.160
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:39:11.160 --> 00:39:15.600
So you went to Burkina Faso
to do a lot of research

00:39:15.600 --> 00:39:18.340
and gather a lot of
evidence and came up

00:39:18.340 --> 00:39:21.740
with the how pride is
universal and even has

00:39:21.740 --> 00:39:25.060
an evolutionary aspect to it.

00:39:25.060 --> 00:39:27.120
What would be the
next step in terms

00:39:27.120 --> 00:39:30.012
of things you want to research?

00:39:30.012 --> 00:39:30.970
JESSICA TRACY: Wow, OK.

00:39:30.970 --> 00:39:36.720
Well, so the Burkina
Faso stuff, that was fun.

00:39:36.720 --> 00:39:39.340
And I think it did actually
lead to a lot of other research

00:39:39.340 --> 00:39:41.240
directions, some of
which are in the book.

00:39:41.240 --> 00:39:44.360
So for example, in
Burkina Faso, we

00:39:44.360 --> 00:39:46.440
found that people
recognized pride.

00:39:46.440 --> 00:39:48.420
But we wanted to know
do people show pride

00:39:48.420 --> 00:39:49.650
the same way in all cultures.

00:39:49.650 --> 00:39:52.017
So we did a study
of the Olympics,

00:39:52.017 --> 00:39:53.600
in which we looked
at Olympic athletes

00:39:53.600 --> 00:39:55.016
from countries all
over the world.

00:39:55.016 --> 00:39:57.420
And this is a great opportunity
to look at pride displays

00:39:57.420 --> 00:40:00.400
because the Olympics is an
occasion where people feel

00:40:00.400 --> 00:40:02.030
a ton of pride if they do well.

00:40:02.030 --> 00:40:04.030
And you have people from
all different countries

00:40:04.030 --> 00:40:05.220
because it's the Olympics.

00:40:05.220 --> 00:40:06.545
And we found that the
same pride display

00:40:06.545 --> 00:40:08.870
is shown by people from
countries all over the world.

00:40:08.870 --> 00:40:11.790
We found no cultural differences
in displays of pride.

00:40:11.790 --> 00:40:13.680
So even people from
collectivistic or Eastern

00:40:13.680 --> 00:40:16.240
cultures were just as likely
to show pride as people

00:40:16.240 --> 00:40:17.836
from Western cultures.

00:40:17.836 --> 00:40:19.460
There was no gender
differences either.

00:40:19.460 --> 00:40:21.150
And then we did a study where
we thought, OK, well, all

00:40:21.150 --> 00:40:22.600
these people, this is great.

00:40:22.600 --> 00:40:24.790
But these are all
professional athletes.

00:40:24.790 --> 00:40:26.360
Unlike our Burkina
Faso participants,

00:40:26.360 --> 00:40:28.990
they have plenty of
exposure to other cultures.

00:40:28.990 --> 00:40:30.740
Maybe they're showing
pride because that's

00:40:30.740 --> 00:40:31.449
our human nature.

00:40:31.449 --> 00:40:33.281
But maybe they're showing
it because they've

00:40:33.281 --> 00:40:35.890
learned when you win an
Olympic medal and you're on TV,

00:40:35.890 --> 00:40:37.490
this is what you're
supposed to do.

00:40:37.490 --> 00:40:39.990
So we were able to
do another study

00:40:39.990 --> 00:40:42.230
of a sample of
individuals who actually

00:40:42.230 --> 00:40:45.210
couldn't have learned to show
pride from watching others.

00:40:45.210 --> 00:40:47.740
And that's because they were
blind athletes, participating

00:40:47.740 --> 00:40:49.220
in the Paralympics Games.

00:40:49.220 --> 00:40:51.270
And so we looked at
these blind athletes,

00:40:51.270 --> 00:40:53.660
including a subsample of
congenitally blind people,

00:40:53.660 --> 00:40:56.954
so people who in their lives had
never seen anyone show pride.

00:40:56.954 --> 00:40:59.120
And when we did that, we
found the exact same thing,

00:40:59.120 --> 00:41:01.203
that even these congenitally
blind athletes who've

00:41:01.203 --> 00:41:02.870
never seen anyone
display pride, when

00:41:02.870 --> 00:41:05.032
they win a match-- and
this was all judo athletes.

00:41:05.032 --> 00:41:07.240
When they win a judo match,
they do that same thing--

00:41:07.240 --> 00:41:09.620
expansive posture,
head tilt up, arms

00:41:09.620 --> 00:41:11.189
extended out from the body.

00:41:11.189 --> 00:41:12.980
So that was kind of
nice evidence, I think.

00:41:12.980 --> 00:41:14.860
And so when I say
pride is universal,

00:41:14.860 --> 00:41:16.360
it's partly because of
the Burkina Faso evidence.

00:41:16.360 --> 00:41:17.901
But it's also things
like this, where

00:41:17.901 --> 00:41:20.100
we're seeing these displays
in such a universal way.

00:41:20.100 --> 00:41:21.450
SPEAKER: OK, if there
are no more questions,

00:41:21.450 --> 00:41:23.376
let's proceed to our
book signing next.

00:41:23.376 --> 00:41:25.000
But first, please
give a warm thank you

00:41:25.000 --> 00:41:26.626
to our author, Jessica Tracy.

